Introduction¶

This is a regression project completed on the Ames Housing Dataset. In this project, I participated in the Kaggle Competition on advanced feature engineering and regression techniques. I conducted analysis on the Ames Housing data set and created several regression models in an attempt to build a predictive model to determine the sale price of homes based on features like square footage, number of bathrooms, etc.This project uses Python 3, Numpy, Pandas, Sci-kit Learn, XGBoost and also showcases some data visualization techniques in Seaborn and Matplotlib. This project required extensive feature extraction/engineering, including imputation of missing data, the creation of aggregate variables, and refactoring categorical variables. I created polynomial features and one-hot encoded the categorical features. I handled skewed features through a boxcox transformation and by scaling the numerical data. I have also included several graphs to help visualize and inspect the data set.

I developed an ensemble model using Lasso based regularized regression models and XGBoost to predict sale prices of homes in Ames, Iowa. My stacked regression ensemble model included regularized regression models, tree based models, and gradient boosted models. I validated my models using root mean squared error and r-squared scores through k-fold cross validation processes. My modeling accounts for over 97% of the variance in sale price. Using a combination of different modeling techniques, I was able to achieve a root mean squared error (a measure of accuracy where 0 would mean 100% accuracy) of 0.12300 on the testing data set (0.11 would get you into the top 10 in the competition).

The full notebook can be viewed on Juptyer's nbviewer and the full project can be downloaded and ran from GitHub.

More info on the Ames Housing Dataset can be found at:

https://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock.pdf

More info on the competition can be found at:

https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques

Creating a function that measures Root Mean Squared Error.¶

In [56]:
def rmse(y_true, y_pred):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
In [57]:
n_folds = 5

def rmse_cv(model):
    kf = KFold(n_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=95).get_n_splits(X_train_scaled.values)
    rmse= np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(model, X_train_scaled, y_train, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv = kf))
    return(rmse)

Creating a regression ensemble¶

In [106]:
# Taking the inverse of the log1p conversion we did on y
kr_preds = np.expm1(kr_pred)
svr_preds = np.expm1(svr_pred)
dtr_preds = np.expm1(dtr_pred)
knn_preds = np.expm1(knn_pred)
xgb_preds = np.expm1(xgb_pred)
abr_preds = np.expm1(abr_pred)
gbr_preds = np.expm1(gbr_pred)
ridge_preds = np.expm1(ridge_pred)
lasso_preds = np.expm1(lasso_pred) 
enet_preds = np.expm1(enet_pred)
etr_preds = np.expm1(etr_pred)
rfr_preds = np.expm1(rfr_pred)
In [107]:
avg_preds = (kr_preds + svr_preds + knn_preds + ridge_preds + abr_preds + log_reg_pred) / 6
In [108]:
agg_preds = (rfr_preds + dtr_preds + etr_preds + avg_preds) / 4
In [109]:
regression_y_predictions = ((lasso_preds * 0.4) + (xgb_preds * 0.3) + (enet_preds * 0.125) + (gbr_preds * 0.125) + (agg_preds * 0.05))

Next Steps¶

Next steps for this project would be to remove some of the more complex feature engineering variables. Since the modesl that performed the best were regualrized, these likely tricked the models into thinking that variables that aren't really all that useful should be used in the final prediction. Another thing I would like to do is develop a better system for outlier detection and removing more outliers. Finally, I would like to build a more sophisticated approach to ensembling by training models on the residuals of previous models.
